I mplementing a planned preventive maintenance system requires the following conditions: 
① Determining the maintenance intervals for assemblies and key components through statistical analysis, measurements, and experimental studies, and rationally categorizing mainten ance tasks; 
② Establishing a set of corresponding technical standards for maintenance teams; 
③ Having well-equipped maintenance facilities organized according to functional divisions and strategically located for optimal efficiency.
The main drawback of the planned preven tive maintenance system is its poor cost-effectiveness. With fixed maintenance cycles and scopes, it often leads to unnecessary repairs of certain components—what’s known as over-m aintenance. During the maintenance process, repairs are categorized into several levels and types based on the depth and breadth of the work required, including major overhauls, mi d-level repairs, minor repairs, item-specific repairs, retrofits, and unplanned maintenance tasks—all determined by the scale and nature of the repair workload.
